	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>The EU commodities plan and cotton-sector initiative are approved</h1>

			
			<h4>
												19 September 2004
										</h4>

					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p> Commission proposals for a commodities action plan and cotton initiative were approved by EU Ministers on April 27th 2004. The main objective of the initiative is to: ‘improve the income of commodity producers in developing countries and reduce the income vulnerability of producers and states due to price fluctuations’.</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p> EU ministers called for priority actions for commodity-dependent countries in the following areas:</p>
<ul>

<li>support to the design and implementation of national commodity-chain strategies; </li>

<li>support to the development of regional markets, policies and support services (linked to the EPA negotiations); </li>

<li>support for diversification, particularly at the level of small producers; </li>

<li>extending access to market-based commodity-risk instruments; </li>

<li>promoting multi-donor cooperation; </li>

<li>paying particular attention to commodities in the current WTO negotiations; </li>

<li>encouraging others to replicate the EU’s EBA initiative; </li>

<li>ensuring resources are provided in the short-term to mitigate the adverse impact on poverty of shortfalls in export earnings; </li>

<li>encouraging sustainable corporate practices; </li>

<li>undertaking assessments of the international commodity bodies and where appropriate making proposals with a view to meeting new challenges.</li>

</ul>
<p> In addition to the current reforms of the EU cotton sector which are under way, the EU’s support strategy for the African cotton sector involves two components:</p>
<ul>

<li>obtaining fairer international trade conditions by: supporting a resolution of the cotton initiative in the WTO; promoting full duty-free access for cotton products; aiming for the elimination of all forms of export subsidies in cotton; undertaking reforms with regard to trade-distorting domestic support;supporting African producers through trade-related technical assistance and capacity building; </li>

<li>supporting cotton-producing countries in Africa by: intensifying co-operation efforts to promote competitiveness; strengthening policies and institutions in the cotton sector; ensuring that the potential of EPAs is fully exploited to support the development of the cotton economies.</li>

</ul>

		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			

<ul>

<li> 
<a href="http://europa.eu.int/comm/agriculture/external/wto/press/ipcotton.pdf" target="_self">EC press release (Brussels, May 5th 2004)</a> </li>

</ul>
		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> The EU’s emphasis on helping commodity producers needs to be seen against the background of the dismantling of the STABEX scheme at the time of the negotiation of the Cotonou Agreement (despite the increasing use of this instrument precisely for this purpose) and the singular failure of the successor FLEX scheme to provide support to east African coffee farmers.. In east Africa efforts to use earlier STABEX transfers to directly compensate coffee farmers for income losses arising from the collapse of prices were firmly resisted by the EC (despite the EU’s own practices with regard to directly assisting producers in the face of a price collapse). It thus remains to be seen how the EU’s current emphasis on improving the income of commodity producers will be put into effect.</p><p> With regard to the support strategy for cotton, there is little new in the EU’s proposals. In terms of access to the EU market LDC cotton producers already enjoy duty-free access under the EBA initiative. For LDCs issues primarily revolve around rules-of-origin questions in the clothing-and-textile sector where mixed fibres are involved. In addition it remains to be seen whether the EU is willing to take action to grant full duty-free access for non-LDC ACP cotton producers. With regard to export subsidies the EU does not provide export subsidies on cotton so no EU action is required in this area. In terms of reform of trade-distorting forms of support the EU already claims it is moving over to non-trade-distorting forms of support in the cotton sector, although World Bank economists have questioned whether the EU’s decoupled farm-payment system is actually non-trade-distorting. It remains to be seen how the EU will respond to these World Bank criticisms. The EU can already use existing Cotonou aid instruments to provide trade-related technical assistance and is in fact increasingly doing so. With regard to intensifying efforts to enhance competitiveness and strengthening institutions and policies, while EU engagement in the latter area is well developed, its record on providing effective assistance to initiatives to enhance industry competitiveness is highly mixed. It thus remains to be seen what benefits will be derived form this dimension of the new EU initiative.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

